# Trader Behavior Analysis Based on Market Sentiment

## Overview
In this project, I analyzed how different market sentiment phases (Fear, Greed, Extreme Greed, Neutral) affect trader behavior and daily performance.  
The motivation was to check whether traders actually perform differently when the market is fearful versus when it is optimistic.

---

## Data Used

### Market Sentiment Data (Fear & Greed Index)
This dataset provides the daily market sentiment classification along with a score and timestamp.  
I used it to label each trading day based on overall market mood.

### Historical Trader Data
This dataset contains individual trader activity such as executed trades, profit or loss, timestamps, and account identifiers.  
It was used to compute daily performance metrics at the trader level.

---

## Approach
I first cleaned both datasets and converted timestamps into a daily date format so they could be aligned.  
For each trader and each day, I calculated:
- Total daily PnL
- Number of trades executed
- Daily win rate

After this, I merged the trader-level daily metrics with the market sentiment of the same day.  
This allowed me to directly compare trader performance across different sentiment conditions.

I also created simple trader segments based on:
- Trading activity (frequent vs infrequent)
- Consistency (based on win rate)

---

## Observations
- Traders tend to earn higher average profits on Fear days, suggesting that volatile or panic-driven markets offer better opportunities.
- Frequent traders generally outperform infrequent traders, especially during Fear and Greed phases.
- Traders with consistent win rates perform more reliably across sentiments, while inconsistent traders struggle during Extreme Greed and Neutral periods.

---

## Practical Takeaways
- Fear-driven markets appear more favorable for active and disciplined traders.
- During Extreme Greed, reducing trade frequency and focusing on higher-quality setups may help control risk.

---

## Limitation
This analysis is based on realized daily PnL only.  
It does not include risk-adjusted metrics, holding duration, or unrealized drawdowns due to data limitations.

